From: Florent Revest <revestflo@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] rtc: pm8xxx: force the aurora RTC read-only

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [aurora-specific HW quirk]

Aurora's (Pixel Watch 2) pm5100 RTC is writable but VOLATILE: it resets to
~epoch (1970) on every cold boot and never retains wall-clock time. The
device tree marks the node "allow-set-time", so userspace time daemons
(dsme/timed) successfully write it, conclude it is a trustworthy clock, and
then slam the system clock to the raw ~1970 RTC value -- clobbering the time
restored at boot by swclock-offset.

Force allow_set_time = false so RTC_SET_TIME returns -EACCES. dsme then takes
its "circumventing read only RTC" delta path (anchored by its mintime floor
and the swclock-offset-seeded system time), keeping correct wall time without
any change to the shared dsme recipe. RTC reads and wakeup alarms do not need
write access, so suspend wakeups keep working.

Signed-off-by: Florent Revest <revestflo@gmail.com>
--- a/drivers/rtc/rtc-pm8xxx.c
+++ b/drivers/rtc/rtc-pm8xxx.c
@@ -656,8 +656,18 @@
 	if (rtc_dd->rtc_alarm_irq < 0)
 		return -ENXIO;
 
-	rtc_dd->allow_set_time = of_property_read_bool(pdev->dev.of_node,
-						      "allow-set-time");
+	/*
+	 * AURORA (Pixel Watch 2): the pm5100 RTC is VOLATILE -- it resets to
+	 * ~epoch on every cold boot and never holds wall-clock time. The
+	 * device tree marks the node "allow-set-time", which lets userspace
+	 * (dsme/timed) write the RTC, conclude it is a trustworthy clock and
+	 * then pull the system clock back to ~1970. Force the RTC read-only
+	 * so RTC_SET_TIME returns -EACCES: dsme's "circumventing read only
+	 * RTC" delta path then keeps correct system time (seeded by
+	 * swclock-offset), while RTC reads and wakeup alarms -- which do not
+	 * need write access -- keep working.
+	 */
+	rtc_dd->allow_set_time = false;
 
 	rtc_dd->regs = match->data;
 	rtc_dd->rtc_dev = &pdev->dev;
